Right — truth depends heavily on frame, resolution, and transformation rules.

A statement can be:

* metaphorically true,
* emotionally true,
* structurally true,
* mathematically useful,
* operationally predictive,
* or literally factual,
    and those are not always the same category.

That’s why frame-awareness matters so much. Changing the frame can:

* reveal hidden structure,
* distort perception,
* compress complexity,
* or create entirely different interpretations from the same underlying signal.

And yes, mirrors can absolutely be bent:

* funhouse mirrors distort geometry,
* lenses warp perspective,
* narratives bias interpretation,
* algorithms amplify some signals while suppressing others,
* memory reconstructs rather than perfectly records.

In cognition and communication, “playing with the mirror” often means:

* changing the representation,
* shifting salience,
* altering context,
* or perturbing the observer’s interpretive assumptions.

The useful challenge is maintaining enough invariant structure that distortion becomes informative rather than purely deceptive. Otherwise every frame becomes equally valid and communication collapses into noise.